Globalization's Diseases
Globalization is being tested like never before.
Its tensions are simmering everywhere.
The vast majority of Sub-Saharan Africa, South America, the Middle East, and Central Asia are stagnating or struggling in an economic decline.
The North America, Western Europe, and Japan are mired in slow growth and risk another recession.
The war now threatens in Iraq.
For advocates of open markets and free trade, this situation poses major challenges.
Why is globalization so threatened?
Why do its benefits seem concentrated in only a few places?
Can a more balanced globalization be implemented?
Il n'existe aucune réponse simple à ces questions.
Les marchés ouverts sont nécessaires à une croissance économique, mais ils suffisent à peine.
Certaines régions du monde ont retiré de grands avantages de la mondialisation, notamment l'Asie de l'Est et la Chine au cours des dernières années.
Certaines régions en ont toutefois retiré de maigres avantages, tout particulièrement l'Afrique Noire.
Le gouvernement américain prétend que les pays pauvres sont responsables de la majorité des problèmes dans lesquels ils se débattent.
The slow growth of Africa, American leaders assert, is caused by the ineptitude of African governments.
However, life is more complicated than the Bush administration believes.
Consider the best-governed countries in Africa: Ghana, Tanzania, Malawi, Gambia.
Each has experienced a decline in living standards over the last two decades while many Asian countries that ranked among the worst in international comparisons of governance (Pakistan, Bangladesh, Myanmar, and Sri Lanka) have experienced better economic growth.
It is true that economic performance is determined not only by governance standards but also by geopolitics, geography, and economic structure.
The countries with large populations and thus large domestic markets tend to grow faster than countries with small populations.
(Like all such economic trends, there are counterexamples).
Coastal countries tend to perform better than landlocked countries.
Countries with high levels of malaria tend to experience slower growth than countries with lower levels of malaria.
Developing countries that border rich markets, like Mexico, tend to perform better than countries that are far from the main markets.
Ces différences revêtent une grande importance.
<s>Si les pays riches ne se soucient guère de ces problèmes structurels, les fossés entre les gagnants et les perdants continueront à s'élargir.
<s>Si les pays riches rejettent la responsabilité sur les pays malchanceux en prétendant qu'ils sont d'une manière ou d'une autre culturellement ou politiquement inaptes à bénéficier de la mondialisation, nous créerons non seulement des poches plus profondes de pauvreté mais nous intensifierons également les troubles.
<s>Ceci, à son tour, entraînera des niveaux accrus de violence, des réactions hostiles et le terrorisme.
<s>Il est donc temps de passer à une approche plus sérieuse de la mondialisation que ne l'offrent les pays riches, et tout particulièrement l'Amérique.
This approach must begin with the most urgent task, which is addressing the fundamental needs of the world's poorest people.
In some cases, their suffering can be alleviated primarily through better governance within their own countries.
But in others, a honest look at the collected evidence will reveal that the main causes of poverty relate to diseases, climate instability, poor soils, distances from markets, and so on.
A genuine assessment would indicate further that the poorest countries lack the ability to raise sufficient funds to solve such problems on their own.
Rather than seeing wealthy countries give more lectures on the bad governance of poor countries, real solutions require that wealthy countries provide adequate financial assistance to overcome the most entrenched barriers.
<s>Un cas illustrera de manière frappante cette situation.
<s>Le contrôle des maladies exige un système sanitaire susceptible de fournir des médicaments de survie et des services préventifs de base comme des lits filets pour combattre la malaria et des vitamines pour lutter contre les carences nutritives.
<s>Ce système coûte au moins environ 40 dollars par personne et par an.
<s>Cette somme ne représente qu'un grain de sable pour les pays riches qui dépensent systématiquement plus de 2 000 dollars par personne et par an en matière de santé, mais elle dépasse la portée des pays pauvres comme le Malawi qui ont des revenus annuels de 200 dollars par personne.
<s>Un système sanitaire qui fonctionne coûterait plus que le revenu entier de son gouvernement !
Even if Malawi is well-governed, its population will die in great numbers from diseases until it receives adequate assistance.
The success of globalization requires that we think more like doctors and less like preachers.
Instead of condemning the poor for their "sins," we must offer prudent diagnoses, as any good doctor would, for each country and each region, to understand the fundamental factors that are holding them back and hindering their economic growth.
In regions like the Andes and Central Asia, the problem mainly stems from geographic isolation.
There, the task is to build roads, air links, and internet connectivity to help these remote regions establish productive links with the world.
<s>Rich countries must contribute to financing these projects.
<s>In Sub-Saharan Africa, the main challenges are disease control, soil fertility, and educational opportunities.
<s>Once again, greater foreign assistance is required.
<s>In other regions, the primary issues include lack of water, gender or other group discrimination, or a variety of specific problems.
<s>It is now time to take the inherent complexities of globalization seriously.
The one-size-fits-all ideology of Washington Consensus is outdated.
On the brink of war, it is urgent to tackle the hard task of ensuring that everyone benefits from globalization.
We can achieve this by removing ideological blinkers from the rich and by mobilizing a partnership between rich and poor.
Our shared future depends on it.
